North Star Dribble Challenge

This week we would like North Star Students and staff to participate in a dribble challenge.

We want all students and staff to find a ball to dribble, a basketball works the best and is the easiest to control, but if you do not have one, use any ball that you have at your house. Every day we would like you to go outside and dribble. Make sure to count the number of times you dribble the ball. When you are done go to the North Star Webpage or Facebook page and record your name, date and number of dribbles on the 1 Million Dribbles Form. Let’s see if we can get to 1 Million this week!

North Star Public School is joining in to turn on stadium lights. We will be turning on the football field lights in Cando on Friday April 3, from 7:00 to 9:30PM as a way to honor our students, staff, and community members in this time of distance learning while school buildings are closed due to Covid-19 concerns.

These lights are a symbol of hope and an assurance that you students are in our hearts and on our minds.

Thanks to our friends at the Minnesota High School Activities Association for the idea!

You can drive by and check it out while social distancing!

post_text:
Attention parents:
Even though summer is almost over, it’s not too late to help your child become a better reader before the new school year begins. Summer is an important time for students to keep reading and improve their language skills. If your child hasn’t been reading regularly this summer, they may be in danger of the “summer slide”—a decline in their reading ability.

Numerous studies indicate that students who don’t read during their summer vacation see their reading abilities decline significantly. This effect becomes more pronounced as students get older and advance through the grade levels. If students don’t read over the summer, they are much more likely to fall behind their peers, widening the “achievement gap” each year.

post_text:
North Star School.During registration students received the North Star meal charging policy, which is requirement by the state.The meal charging policy was also discussed at the Back to School Night.Basically what the policy states is that meals will be pre-paid for and if a meal balance reaches zero or a negative balance you will be notified by the school.

The school will begin checking meal balances and notifying parents every Friday beginning September 8th.If your child has been eating at the school and you have not pre-paid please do so as soon as possible.You may pay in the main office by check or with cash or you may pay online with a credit/debit card or have a payment withdrawn from your bank account.

Directions on how to pay online were handed out at registration and are also in the August newsletter on the schools website.
If you have any questions contact the school.
